  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'GeodesicManifold-Refine' that integrates spherical coordinate perturbation and pixelwise depth intervals within a geodesically regularized Riemannian optimization paradigm to refine depth and normal estimates in textureless regions. The core innovation lies in embedding the 3D surface reconstruction problem into a joint geometric manifold where local spherical perturbations are constrained by globally propagated geodesic distances derived from semantic seeds. Unlike prior methods that rely solely on photometric consistency or local smoothness, our approach leverages the intrinsic geometry of surfaces—captured via learned geodesic embeddings—to guide refinement in areas devoid of texture. Specifically, we first generate initial depth and normal maps using a standard MVS pipeline (e.g., CasMVSNet). Then, using Segment Anything Model (SAM) outputs, we identify coherent semantic regions and select seed points within each to initiate differentiable geodesic distance propagation over the estimated surface using a neural Eikonal solver. These geodesic maps encode intrinsic surface structure and are used to modulate both spherical perturbations and depth interval adjustments. For instance, during normal refinement, perturbations in spherical coordinates (θ, φ) are penalized if they induce excessive deviation from parallel transport along geodesic paths, ensuring orientation coherence across extended surfaces. Similarly, depth intervals are expanded or contracted not only based on local uncertainty but also on geodesic proximity to boundaries—regions far from edges in geodesic space allow larger, more confident updates. A key component is the introduction of a Riemannian gradient descent scheme where the metric tensor is dynamically estimated from local surface curvature and geodesic dispersion, enabling adaptive step sizes that respect the underlying manifold geometry. This eliminates the need for hand-tuned parameters or EM-style calibration. Moreover, we introduce a coupled PDE system: the geodesic map evolves according to the updated normal field via covariant differentiation, while the normal field is updated using geodesic-curvature regularization derived from second-order geodesic variations. This closed-loop interaction ensures that refinement enhances both local accuracy and global plausibility. To train and evaluate, we design a loss function combining photometric reprojection error, geodesic Laplacian smoothness, and normal-depth consistency enforced through finite differences on the manifold. Our method significantly improves reconstruction fidelity on large planar and smoothly curved textureless surfaces such as ceilings, furniture, and human skin, reducing artifacts like over-smoothing and geometric tearing. It generalizes well to sparse-view settings and performs robustly across diverse datasets including ScanNet, ETH3D, and Human3.6M, achieving state-of-the-art results in both RMSE and geodesic-aware evaluation metrics.",
